 That 's what the man had said .

VII) a manservant who acts as a personal attendant to his employer

IX) one of the British Isles in the Irish Sea
X) game equipment consisting of an object used in playing certain board games
XI) all of the living human inhabitants of the earth

Do not provide explanations. Just output the choice.
RESULT:  III) The generic use of the word to refer to any human being.
The answer is: III
Gold answer is: 1

RESULT:  B) The correct sense for the phrase "As a matter of fact" in the given text is:

The answer is: I
Gold answer is: -1

II) (quantifier used with mass nouns) small in quantity or degree; not much or almost none or (with `a') at least some
III) (of children and animals) young, immature
IV) (informal) small and of little importance
V) (of a voice) faint
VI) low in stature; not tall
VII) lowercase
VIII) small in a way that arouses feelings (of tenderness or its opposite depending on the context)

I) national; especially in reference to the government of the United States as distinct from that of its member units
II) of or relating to the central government of a federation
III) being of or having to do with the northern United States and those loyal to the Union during the American Civil War
IV) characterized by or constituting a form of government in which power is divided between one central and several regional authorities

Do not provide explanations. Just output the choice.
RESULT:  II) Of or relating to the central government of a federation.
The answer is: II

PROMPT: Which of the following senses is correct for the word "theory" in the following text:

 To the extent that the primary duty of personal staff involves local benefit-seeking , this indicates that political philosophy leads congressional Republicans to pay less attention to narrow constituent concerns .

I) a belief (or system of beliefs) accepted as authoritative by some group or school
II) the rational investigation of questions about existence and knowledge and ethics
III) any personal belief about how to live or how to deal with a situation

 The quake knocked The Well out for six hours , but when it came back up , it teemed with emotional first-hand reports .

I) a period of time assigned for work
II) an indefinite period of time
III) a period of time equal to 1/24th of a day
IV) clock time
V) a special and memorable period
VI) distance measured by the time taken to cover it

Do not provide explanations. Just output the choice.
RESULT:  III) a period of time equal to 1/24th of a day
The answer is: III
Gold answer is: 3
Attempted: 1241, Correct: 656, Accuracy: 0.5286059629331185

 I was in my favorite watering hole , waiting for the game to start .

I) take the first step or steps in carrying out an action
II) set in motion, cause to start
III) leave
IV) have a beginning, in a temporal, spatial, or evaluative sense
V) bring into being
VI) get off the ground
VII) move or jump suddenly, as if in surprise or alarm
VIII) get going or set in motion
IX) begin or set in motion
X) begin work or acting in a certain capacity, office or job
XI) play in the starting lineup
XII) have a beginning characterized in some specified way
XIII) begin an event that is implied and limited by the nature or inherent function of the direct object
XIV) bulge outward

Do not provide explanations. Just output the choice.
RESULT:  The correct sense of the word "start" in the given context is:

I) take the first step or steps in carrying out an action
The answer is: I
Gold answer is: 1
